<paragraph base="F16150269" principles="no" id="IAS19_66"><paranum>66</paranum><prolog><data name="standard_number" value="IAS 19"/><data name="paranum" value="66"/></prolog><body><p id="IAS19_P0275">The ultimate cost of a <xref base="F16149637" href="IAS19_0002.dita#IAS19_0002/IAS19_UN0008">defined benefit plan<ph outputclass="def_xref"><xref keyref="GLOSSARY_DI0078"/></ph></xref> may be influenced by many variables, such as final salaries, employee turnover and mortality, employee contributions and medical cost trends. The ultimate cost of the plan is uncertain and this uncertainty is likely to persist over a long period of time. In order to measure the present value of the <xref base="F16148491" href="IAS19_0001.dita#IAS19_0001/IAS19_UN0003">post&#x2011;employment benefit<ph outputclass="def_xref"><xref keyref="GLOSSARY_DI0292"/></ph></xref> obligations and the related <xref base="F16149753" href="IAS19_0004.dita#IAS19_0004/IAS19_UN0018">current service cost<ph outputclass="def_xref"><xref keyref="GLOSSARY_DI0068"/></ph></xref>, it is necessary:</p><ol base="F16150271" type="lower-alpha" id="IAS19_L0047"><li><li_value>(a)</li_value>         <p base="F16150272" id="IAS19_P0276">to apply an actuarial valuation method (see <xref base="F16227305" href="IAS19_g67-69.dita#IAS19_g67-69" id="IAS19_X0324">paragraphs 67&#x2013;69</xref>);</p>       </li><li><li_value>(b)</li_value>         <p base="F16150274" id="IAS19_P0277">to attribute benefit to periods of service (see <xref base="F16227309" href="IAS19_g70-70.dita" id="IAS19_X0325">paragraphs 70&#x2013;74</xref>); and</p>       </li><li><li_value>(c)</li_value>         <p base="F16150276" id="IAS19_P0278">to make actuarial assumptions (see <xref base="F16227310" href="IAS19_75.dita#IAS19_75" id="IAS19_X0326">paragraphs 75&#x2013;98</xref>).</p>       </li></ol></body></paragraph>